\pard The 3V3 supplies on Pin 7 are not short-circuit protected\f0  (other than any protection given by the regulator)\f1 .  This allows built-in electronics such as rapid fire circuits to have the best chance of operating.\f0  \f1 The Pin 6 supplies pins are current limited to 22mA each.\f0  as these will be shorted to GND by Fire / Trigger buttons. \f1 All joystick switch inputs are active-low.\par
\par
The Controller use\f0 s\f1  Data, Latch and Clock lines. \f0 It is\f1  similar to those used for the NES/Famicom\f0  types in operation \f1  but ha\f0 s a\f1  DB9\f0 F\f1  plug. They are obtainable from Aliexpress at very reasonable cost. You can also build your own as the components (if you use ordinary buttons) are inexpensive.\f0  There is one CD4021B parallel/serial shift register chip, 8 10k resistors and 8 buttons.\par
\f1\par
Several variations of joysticks can be used:\par
Atari 800/VCS has switches, Pad A and Pad B. There is a single Fire button as above.\par
Atari ST is switched only. It has an additional button on pin 9\par
Commodore Amiga, Vic20, C64 & C128 have switches, Pot X (Button 2) & Pot Y (Button 3). Pin 6 is Button 1.\par
\par
Do not use joysticks intended for the built-in ports on the Sinclair Spectrum +2, +2A or +3. These are wired differently and are incompatible.\par
\f0\page A  small self-contained RTC module can be installed if required. On this system it uses two of the signals (GP15 and GP22) that were previously used for Port B so it does not affect the availability of the analogue inputs on the controller port. Even if you don't want it now it's worth fitting the 5-pin male header for it as you can always plug the RTC in later should you change your mind.\par
\par
The filter used in the audio section was designed by Volhout, and is far better than the usual one. This has a flat response up to about 19kHz, where it starts to descend steeply to filter out most of the high level 44kHz PWM carrier. The resulting audio quality is excellent. R23 and R24 can be increased in value or omitted if the user finds that there is insufficient output (it can drive 32R headphones or a line output at 0.5V RMS).\par
\par
The 2.2mH inductors should be the specified part. It is possible to use others, but you may have to find new capacitor values to tune them correctly and good results cannot be guaranteed. Additionally, some simply will not fit in the available space even if they are of the correct value. There is a little spare space around these components and the tuning capacitors C8 & C9  to allow some experimentation.\par
\par
If you would rather use the original audio filter for some reason then this can also be accommodated:\par
Change R19 and R20 to 1k\par
Link out L1 and L2\par
Omit C8 , C9, C10 and C11\par
Change R21, R22, R23 and R24 to 2K2\par
Optionally, link out C12 and C13 and omit R25 and R26\par
This filter is not recommended if you are going to feed an amplifier and good quality speakers as there is far too much 44kHz content in the signal, which could in some cases damage tweeters. It is useful if you want to use these outputs as analogue PWM outputs instead of audio though.\par
\par
The assembly fits a common, very low cost case 90mm x 70mm x 28mm which is available from several ebay suppliers. These cases very rarely come with screws. You will need self tapping screws  No.4 x 1/4" (2.9mm x 6mm) to fasten the PCB into the case and No.2 x 3/8" (2.2mm x 9.5mm) to hold the case together. Note that the case halves will only fit one way round. Mark them on the inside to make sure that everything will line up.\par
\par
A 1mm diameter hole near the bottom of R26 marks the position of the LED on the PicoMite. If the bare PCB is first fitted into the TOP of the case, with the top side of the PCB against the case, then you can use this hole as a guide to drill the top of the case for the indicator. (The LED will actually end up inside the case, below the hole. There may be some scope for making a short light guide out of fishing line, a tiny nylon screw or something like that.) \par
\par
The PCB is supplied with the front and back case panels attached. It is, of course, necessary to cut these off. I find that the best way is to put a panel part into a vice (I use some pieces of aluminium angle in the jaws to give some protection as you need to grip it quite tightly), with the top of the jaws along the cutting line. Then score several times with a sharp craft knife on both sides, using the top of the jaws as a guide. I then push the pcb over using a piece of wood and it will snap along the scored line. Clean up both edges with a file (Warning! Fibreglass particles are an irritant - at least wear a dust mask!) then do the other side. \par
\page Assembly should be reasonably straightforward with the exception of the surface-mounted micro-SD connector. Even this shouldn't be terribly difficult, but is best done with solder paste, gel flux and a heat gun. If you don't have a heat gun then get one (if you ever unsolder components or use heat shrink tube then you'll wonder why you hadn't got one already) - this is a good excuse and they are remarkably cheap!  Mount this component first as it is difficult to work around and it removes the likelihood of damaging components around it.  I apologise for not using some sort of easily solderable module here, but there simply wasn't enough space. :)  Fit the low level components first as it makes things easier.\par
\par
By default 5V power is supplied via a 3.5mm barrel jack socket and a polarity protection diode. However, a solder-blob link beneath the board can be changed to obtain the 5V supply from the VBUS pin of the PicoMite, allowing power to be obtained solely from the USB connector. Note that this probably won't be possible for mechanical reasons if the unit is housed in the recommended case as the USB connector is against the top of the case. For those who really insist, 3V3EN is linked to GND using another solder-blob link which can be cut to enable the PicoMite's SMPS. Do not do this if U1 is fitted. You will probably introduce noise onto the audio by using the SMPS.\par
\par
The link block \f1 has the middle \f0 two \f1 pins connected to the analogue inputs \f0 GP26 and GP27 \f1 via 10k resistors. It can be used in 3 ways:\par
\par
With no link - the analogue pin is simply connected to the port. An input voltage is provided by a potentiometer between GND and 3V3.\par
With the link set to U the resistor is connected as a pull-up to 3V3. This allows the input to be used for an active-low button input. e.g. for joysticks that have multiple buttons like the Atari ST.\par
With the link set to D the resistor is connected as a pull-down to GND. This is the usual connection when a "Paddle" is used. They have one end connected to 3V3 and the other to the analogue input.\par
\f0\par
